'''''Allegory of Fortune''''', sometimes also named '''''La Fortuna''''', is an oil painting on canvas, that was created around 1658 or 1659, by the Italian baroque painter [[Salvator Rosa]], which caused uproar when first exhibited publicly and almost got the painter jailed and excommunicated. Bearing initials but undated, it measures {{convert|200.7|by|133|cm|in}}. Rosa was known for his landscape paintings, but also worked in the sphere of mythology, witchcraft, portraits, and satire.{{r|Dulwich}} Since 1978 it has been in the [[J. Paul Getty Museum]] in [[Malibu, California]].

==Background==
The painting was made at much the same time as Rosa penned ''Babilonia'', a satirical condemnation of the papal court.{{r|Sewell}}{{efn|''Babilonia'' was the term Rosa used when referring to Rome.{{sfnp|Fredericksen1991|p=543|ps=}}}} According to art critic [[Brian Sewell]], the target of the satirical painting could not be misinterpreted.{{r|Sewell}} Rosa's friends warned him after viewing it privately,{{sfnp|Fredericksen|1980|p=18|ps=}} that the painting should not be displayed openly as it was a satirical attack on [[Pope Alexander VII]]'s patronage.{{r|Grove}} In 1659, the painting was exhibited at the [[Pantheon, Rome]], which almost resulted in Rosa being jailed and [[excommunicated]]. Only the intervention of the pope's brother, Don Marco Chigi, saved him from this humiliation.{{sfnp|Fredericksen|1980|p=18|ps=}}

Eventually, Rosa was convinced of the need to offer an explanation of the picture; he did this under the rubric of ''Manifesto'' and, according to art writer [[James Elmes]], "proved that his hogs were not churchmen, his mules pretending pedants, his asses Roman nobles, and his birds and beasts of prey, the reigning despots of Italy."{{sfnp|Elmes|1825|p=92|ps=}}

An earlier painting of Fortune was undertaken by Rosa during the 1640s.{{sfnp|Roworth|1975|p=663|ps=}}

==Description==
The overall dimensions of the undated oil on canvas are {{convert|200.7|x|133|cm|in}} wide;{{r|Art Project}} the initials "SR" inscribed on the book at the lower left represent the signature of the artist.{{r|Getty}} The painting, sometimes referred to as ''La Fortuna'',{{sfnp|Viers|2008|p=86|ps=}} depicts [[Fortuna]], the goddess of fortune and personification of [[luck]], pouring her gifts on an array of undeserving animals. Traditionally Fortuna has her eyes covered and the vessel containing her favours, the horn of plenty or [[Cornucopia]], is shown in an upright position; Rosa has reversed this tradition in his rendition and portrays Fortuna completely acquainted with where and on whom she is bestowing her gifts from the upended cornucopia.{{r|Art Project}}

Gemstones, coronets, a sceptre, gold coins, pearls, roses, together with grapes, cereal, and berries flow from the cornucopia onto the animals below.{{sfnp|Roworth|1975|p=664|ps=}} In turn the animals are stamping on the symbols of education, the [[art]]s, and knowledge. The donkey, the symbol of the pope, wearing a  cardinal's red and gold coat as a drapery, is suppressing and casting a shadow on an [[owl]], used here as the symbol for [[wisdom]]. The painting is expressing the artist's feelings of bitterness about the fact he lost the papal patronage, and thus Rosa included personal references: a rose signifies Rosa's name; a [[Palette (painting)|palette]] is placed on the book, and the book carries his initials. A pig stepping on a rose also symbolizes the same thing.{{r|Art Project}}

==Exhibitions and provenance==
[[File:Dosso Dossi (Giovanni di Niccolò de Lutero) (Italian (Ferrarese) - Allegory of Fortune - Google Art Project.jpg|thumbnail|upright| [[Dosso Dossi]], Allegory of Fortune showing the cornucopia depicted upright, as usual]]
After being displayed in 1659, the painting was acquired by Carlo de Rossi and on his death in around 1683 became the property of Antonio Vallori.{{r|Getty}}

It moved from Italy to England after Vallori sold it to [[Henry Scudamore, 3rd Duke of Beaufort]] in 1727{{sfnp|Roworth|1975|p=663|ps=}} for six hundred [[Italian scudo|scudi]].{{sfnp|Morgan|1824|p=16|ps=}} The duke was completing a [[Grand Tour]] and purchased two Rosa paintings, the other one entitled, ''Nursing of Jupiter''.{{sfnp|Nicolson|1957|p=416|ps=}} Passed down by inheritance, the Fortune painting remained in the possession of the various [[Dukes of Beaufort]] until sold by the [[Henry Somerset, 10th Duke of Beaufort|tenth duke]] in 1957, when it was purchased by [[Marlborough Fine Art|the Marlborough Gallery]]. It was acquired by [[J. Paul Getty]] from the gallery in 1971.{{r|Getty}} Until it passed to the Getty Museum in 1978 it was only exhibited three times: from 21 May 1827 at the Bristol Institution; at the [[British Institution]] in 1859; and as part of the J. Paul Getty Collection exhibition in the summer of 1972 at the [[Minneapolis Institute of Arts]]. In the twenty-first century it has been displayed as part of the ''Bandits, Wilderness and Magic'' exhibition firstly at [[Dulwich Picture Gallery]] in London during 2010 and at the [[Kimbell Art Museum]] in Texas from the end of December 2010 to March 2011.{{r|Getty}}

